DESCRIPTION: The difference between the latitude values of a point in the target and source coordinate reference systems.
The difference between the longitude values of a point in the target and source coordinate reference systems.
The difference between the height or depth values of a point in the target and source coordinate reference systems.

The height of the geoid above a specified ellipsoid.  Indicated by symbol N.  Usually interpolated within a geoid model.
N = h - H, where h is the height above the ellipsoid and H is the gravity-related height.
The difference between the X values of a point in the target and source coordinate reference systems.
The difference between the Y values of a point in the target and source coordinate reference systems.
The difference between the Z values of a point in the target and source coordinate reference systems.

The angular difference between the Y and Z axes directions of target and source coordinate reference systems. This is a rotation about the X axis as viewed from the origin looking along that axis. The particular method defines which direction is positive, and what is being rotated (point or axis).

The angular difference between the X and Z axes directions of target and source coordinate reference systems. This is a rotation about theY axis as viewed from the origin looking along that axis. The particular method defines which direction is positive, and what is being rotated (point or axis).

The angular difference between the X and Y axes directions of target and source coordinate reference systems. This is a rotation about the Z axis as viewed from the origin looking along that axis. The particular method defines which direction is positive, and what is being rotated (point or axis).

The scale difference increased by unity equals the ratio of an the length of an arbitrary distance between two points in target and source coordinate reference systems.  This is usually averaged for the intersection area of the two coordinate reference systems. 

If a distance of 100 km in the source coordinate reference system translates into a distance of 100.001 km in the target coordinate reference system, the scale difference is 1 ppm (the ratio being 1.000001).

PARAMETER_NAME: Scale factor for source coordinate reference system first axis
DESCRIPTION: The unit of measure of the source coordinate reference system first axis, expressed in the unit of measure of the target coordinate reference system.

PARAMETER_NAME: Scale factor for source coordinate reference system second axis
DESCRIPTION: The unit of measure of the source coordinate reference system second axis, expressed in the unit of measure of the target coordinate reference system

PARAMETER_NAME: Rotation angle of source coordinate reference system axes
DESCRIPTION:
Angle (counter-clockwise positive) through which both of the source coordinate reference system axes need to rotated to coincide with the corresponding target coordinate reference system axes.  

Alternatively, the bearing (clockwise positive) of the source coordinate reference system YS-axis measured relative to target coordinate reference system north.

PARAMETER_NAME: Rotation angle of source coordinate reference system first axis
DESCRIPTION: Angle (counter-clockwise positive) through which the source coordinate reference system's first axis needs to rotated to coincide with the corresponding axis of the target coordinate reference system.

PARAMETER_NAME: Rotation angle of source coordinate reference system second axis
DESCRIPTION: Angle (counter-clockwise positive) through which the source coordinate reference system's second axis needs to rotated to coincide with the corresponding axis of the target coordinate reference system.
The value of the first ordinate value of the evaluation point.
The value of the second ordinate of the evaluation point.

DESCRIPTION: The value of the first ordinate of the evaluation point expressed in the source coordinate reference system.

PARAMETER_NAME: Ordinate 2 of evaluation point in source CRS

PARAMETER_NAME: Ordinate 1 of evaluation point in target CRS
DESCRIPTION: The value of the first ordinate of the evaluation point expressed in the target coordinate reference system.  In the case of an affine transformation the evaluation point is the origin of the source coordinate reference system.

PARAMETER_NAME: Ordinate 2 of evaluation point in target CRS
DESCRIPTION: The value of the second ordinate of the evaluation point expressed in the target coordinate reference system.  In the case of an affine transformation the evaluation point is the origin of the source coordinate reference system.

Coordinate differences at control points
The name of the [path and] file containing geoid heights.
The value of the third ordinate of the evaluation point.

The latitude of the point from which the values of both the geographical coordinates on the ellipsoid and the grid coordinates on the projection are deemed to increment or decrement for computational purposes. Alternatively it may be considered as the latitude of the point which in the absence of application of false coordinates has grid coordinates of (0,0).

The longitude of the point from which the values of both the geographical coordinates on the ellipsoid and the grid coordinates on the projection are deemed to increment or decrement for computational purposes. Alternatively it may be considered as the longitude of the point which in the absence of application of false coordinates has grid coordinates of (0,0).  Sometimes known as "central meridian (CM)".
The factor by which the map grid is reduced or enlarged during the projection process, defined by its value at the natural origin.

Since the natural origin may be at or near the centre of the projection and under normal coordinate circumstances would thus give rise to negative coordinates over parts of the mapped area, this origin is usually given false coordinates which are large enough to avoid this inconvenience. The False Easting, FE, is the value assigned to the abscissa (east or west) axis of the projection grid at the natural origin.

Since the natural origin may be at or near the centre of the projection and under normal coordinate circumstances would thus give rise to negative coordinates over parts of the mapped area, this origin is usually given false coordinates which are large enough to avoid this inconvenience. The False Northing, FN, is the value assigned to the ordinate (north or south) axis of the projection grid at the natural origin.
For an oblique projection, this is the latitude of the point at which the azimuth of the central line is defined.
For an oblique projection, this is the longitude of the point at which the azimuth of the central line is defined.
The azimuthal direction (north zero, east of north being positive) of the great circle which is the centre line of an oblique projection. The azimuth is given at the projection center.

PARAMETER_NAME: Angle from Rectified to Skew Grid
DESCRIPTION: The angle at the natural origin of an oblique projection through which the natural coordinate reference system is rotated to make the projection north axis parallel with true north.
The factor by which the map grid is reduced or enlarged during the projection process, defined by its value at the projection center.
The easting value assigned to the projection centre.
The northing value assigned to the projection centre.

Latitude of the parallel on which the conic or cylindrical projection is based.  This latitude is not geographic, but is defined on the conformal sphere AFTER its rotation to obtain the oblique aspect of the projection

PARAMETER_NAME: Scale factor on pseudo standard parallel
DESCRIPTION: The factor by which the map grid is reduced or enlarged during the projection process, defined by its value at the pseudo-standard parallel.
The latitude of the point which is not the natural origin and at which grid coordinate values false easting and false northing are defined.
The longitude of the point which is not the natural origin and at which grid coordinate values false easting and false northing are defined.
For a conic projection with two standard parallels, this is the latitude of intersection of the cone with the ellipsoid that is nearest the pole.  Scale is true along this parallel.
For a conic projection with two standard parallels, this is the latitude of intersection of the cone with the ellipsoid that is furthest from the pole.  Scale is true along this parallel.
The easting value assigned to the false origin.
The northing value assigned to the false origin.

The latitude of the point from which the values of both the geographical coordinates on the sphere and the grid coordinates on a spherical projection are deemed to increment or decrement for computational purposes.

The longitude of the point from which the values of both the geographical coordinates on the sphere and the grid coordinates on a spherical projection are deemed to increment or decrement for computational purposes.
The longitude of the western limit of the first zone of a Transverse Mercator zoned grid system.
The longitude width of a zone of a Transverse Mercator zoned grid system.
